title: Kullback-Leibler Barycentre of Stochastic Processes

sections.text:
#### Abstract

We consider the problem where an agent aims to combine the views and insights of different experts' models. Specifically, each expert proposes a diffusion process over a finite time horizon. The agent then combines the experts' models by minimising the weighted Kullback-Leibler divergence to each of the experts' models. We show existence and uniqueness of the barycentre model and prove an explicit representation of the Radon-Nikodym derivative relative to the average drift model. We further allow the agent to include their own constraints, resulting in an optimal model that can be seen as a distortion of the experts' barycentre model to incorporate the agent's constraints. We propose two deep learning algorithms to approximate the optimal drift of the combined model, allowing for efficient simulations. The first algorithm aims at learning the optimal drift by matching the change of measure, whereas the second algorithm leverages the notion of elicitability to directly estimate the value function. The paper concludes with an extended application to combine implied volatility smile models that were estimated on different datasets.


Key words. Mixtures of Experts, Kullback-Leibler, Barycentre, Model Combination, Ensemble Model, Deep learning, Elicitability, Volatility Smiles

1. Introduction. In many situations a modeller or agent aims to find a single model to, e.g., predict, forecast, classify, or approximate observed patterns. While model selection procedures provide rankings of the different models' performances - thus allowing the agent to select one model - an alternative to disregarding all but one model is model combination. In the statistical literature, so-called forecast ensemble or superensemble models have been widely applied to weather prediction as they are known to improve deterministic forecasts, see e.g., [14] and reference therein. A variant of a statistical superensemble that allows for predictive distribution functions is to regress a quantity of interest (e.g., air pressure, temperature) onto forecasts stemming from different models [14]. Averaging different predictions has also been used in machine learning, where early examples include bagging predictors [7], Adaptive, Reweighting and Combining (ARCing) algorithms and Adaboost [8]. To improve the architecture of neural networks, [16] propose neural networks ensembles (averaging different neural network architectures), which have been applied in, e.g., credit scoring [26] and oil price forecasting [27]. We also refer to [21] for an application to fusion of generative models.

This work focuses on model combinations of dynamic stochastic models in continuoustime. A related stream of literature, though in discrete-time, is called dynamic time warping

(see e.g., [5]), which aims at matching or detecting similarities in time series data by finding a "warping path" that minimises a distance between the time series. Applications of dynamic time warping are widespread and range from classification of genome signals [25], to speech recognition [19], and clustering of financial stocks [12].

Differently from dynamic time warping, which is a data driven approach based on time series sample paths, we propose to average different dynamics of stochastic processes. Furthermore, while most model averaging methodologies optimise for the weights to be associated with each model, in our setting the weights are given. Thus, a key contribution of this work is to characterise the dynamics of the stochastic process that minimises a weighted distance to each model, that is finding the stochastic barycentre model.

In this manuscript, we consider a finite number of experts, each having their own belief about the dynamics of a continuous-time diffusion process. The experts' models are characterised by different probability measures, under which the process follows the experts' dynamics. An agent then aims at combining the different experts' models by finding the probability measure that minimises the weighted Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence to all models. The resulting dynamics of the stochastic process is described by the barycentre model. Moreover, we allow the agent to include their own views, described by expectations of functions of the terminal values of the process or expected running cost, which results in a constrained barycentre model. Key contributions of this work are as follows. First, we derive the optimal value function of our optimisation problem and a succinct representation of the Radon-Nikodym (RN) derivative of the optimal probability measure to, what we term, the average drift measure. We find that the optimal RN derivative is of Escher type albeit different to the classical solution of maximum entropy, see e.g., [11]. Second, we prove that our constraint optimisation problem is equivalent to an optimisation problem of distorting the expert's barycentre model to include the agent's constraints. The latter optimisation problem, that is distorting stochastic processes to include constraints has been studied in [20] and [18]. Third, we propose two deep learning algorithms to approximate the optimal probability measure and thus the dynamics of the constrained barycentre process, allowing for simulation under the constrained barycentre model. Fourth, we apply our framework to combining implied volatility smile models that were estimated on different sets of real data.

Here, we utilise the KL divergence to quantify divergences between probability measures on the path space of stochastic processes. Alternatives could be distances on the space of probability measures stemming from optimal transport theory, such as the Wasserstein distance. There are, however, two caveats: first, calculating a Wasserstein barycentre between random variables is in general an NP hard problem [2], highlighting the curse of dimensionality associated with the Wasserstein distance; second, as we work in continuous time and over a finite time horizon, the Wasserstein distance needs to be replaced with the adapted (also called bicausal) Wasserstein distance. The adapted Wasserstein distance between stochastic processes is only known in special cases $[6,3,15,24]$, and most recent results on barycentre with adapted Wasserstein barycentre pertain to existence and uniqueness [4, 1], while with the KL divergence we obtain a closed-form solution of the optimal RN derivative for arbitrary dimension of the stochastic process.

The manuscript is structured as follows. Section 2 introduces the experts' models and the agent's optimisation problem (P). Section 3 establishes the solution to the pure barycentre.

In Subsection 3.1 we consider the special case of two expert models and in Subsection 3.2 the special case of Ornstein-Uhlenbeck processes. The solution to the KL barycentre with beliefs is detailed in Section 4. Key results are the concise representation of the optimal change of measure (Proposition 4.4) and the recasting of optimisation problem (P) into an optimisation problem of minimally distorting the barycentre measure to include the agent's constraints (Proposition 4.5). In Section 5, we propose two deep learning algorithms to approximate the drift of the optimally combined model. Subsection 6.1 illustrates and compares these algorithms on simulated examples. A financial application to combining implied volatility smiles models, that were estimated on different datasets, is provided in Subsection 6.2.
2. Constrained Kullback-Leibler barycentre. This section first introduces the experts' models and the optimisation problem - minimising the weighted KL divergence between the experts' models with constraints - that the agent aims to tackle. Second, using a stochastic control approach, we solve the optimisation problem and characterise the optimal model. Third, we relate the optimisation problem to a modified barycentre model, in the spirit of $[18]$.
2.1. Experts' opinions and agent's problem. We work on a complete and filtered probability space, denoted by $\left(\Omega, \mathbb{P}, \mathcal{F},\left(\mathcal{F}_{t}\right)_{t \in[0, T]}\right)$, satisfying the usual conditions of right continuity, on which we have a $d$-dimensional Brownian motion $B=\left(B_{t}\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$ (with independent components) and the filtration is the natural one generated by $B$. We further have a $d$ dimensional process $X=\left(X_{t}\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$, that the agent is interested in modelling, and a set of experts $\mathcal{K}:=\{1, \ldots, K\}$. Each expert $k \in \mathcal{K}$ has a probability measure $\mathbb{P}^{(k)}$ - called the "model" of expert $k$ - which is equivalent to $\mathbb{P}\left(\mathbb{P} \sim \mathbb{P}^{(k)}\right.$ ), and believes that under $\mathbb{P}^{(k)}$ the process $X$ satisfies the stochastic differential equation (SDE)

$$
\mathrm{d} X_{t}=\mu^{(k)}\left(t, X_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} t+\sigma\left(t, X_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} W_{t}^{(k)}
$$

where $W^{(k)}=\left(W_{t}^{(k)}\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$ denotes a $d$-dimensional $\mathbb{P}^{(k)}$-Brownian motion, $\mu^{(k)}(t, x): \mathbb{R}_{+} \times$ $\mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{d}$ the drift, and $\sigma(t, x): \mathbb{R}_{+} \times \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathrm{~S}_{++}^{d}$, where $\mathrm{S}_{++}^{d}$ is the set of $d$-dimensional matrices such that (s.t.) $\sigma^{\top} \sigma$ is strictly positive definite, the volatility. That is, each expert has a different view on the drift of the process $X$. If the experts had differing views on the volatility, so that expert $-k$ wanted a diffusion coefficient of $\sigma^{(k)}\left(t, X_{t}\right)$, then the KL divergence between the experts' models is infinite, and hence we could not meaningfully determine a weighted KL barycentre model. Instead, one could regularise the problem, by e.g., introducing a new process $Y=\left(Y_{t}\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$ and a new Brownian motion $B^{Y}$ (independent of all others) that mean-reverts to $\sigma^{(k)}\left(t, X_{t}\right)$. Then the expert model could be defined as

$$
\begin{gathered}
\mathrm{d} X_{t}=\mu^{(k)}\left(t, X_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} t+Y_{t} \mathrm{~d} W_{t}^{(k)} \\
\mathrm{d} Y_{t}=\frac{1}{\varepsilon}\left(\sigma^{(k)}\left(t, X_{t}\right)-Y_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} t+\mathrm{d} W_{t}^{Y(k)}
\end{gathered}
$$

where $W^{Y(k)}$ is a $\mathbb{P}^{(k)}$-Brownian motion independent of the other Brownian motions $W^{(k)}$. As $\varepsilon \downarrow 0$, the process $Y$ is pinned to $\sigma^{(k)}\left(t, X_{t}\right)$. In this manner, the setting where experts have differing volatilities may be cast into our original setting by increasing the state space dimension by 1 .

Returning now to our original setting, the next set of assumptions guarantee that a strong solution to (2.1) exists.

Assumption 2.1. The functions $\mu^{(k)}(\cdot, \cdot)$, for all $k \in \mathcal{K}$, and $\sigma(\cdot, \cdot)$ satisfy the linear growth and Lipschitz continuity conditions. That is here exists a constant $C_{1}<\infty$, such that for all $t \in[0, T]$ and all $x \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$,

$$
\|\sigma(t, x)\|^{2}+\left|\mu^{(k)}(t, x)\right|^{2} \leq C_{1}\left(1+|x|^{2}\right)
$$

where $|\cdot|$ denotes the Euclidean norm and $\|\cdot\|$ the Frobenius norm. Moreover, there exists a constant $C_{2}<\infty$, such that for all $t \in[0, T]$ and all $x, y \in \mathbb{R}^{d}$,

$$
\|\sigma(t, x)-\sigma(t, y)\|^{2}+\left|\mu^{(k)}(t, x)-\mu^{(k)}(t, y)\right|^{2} \leq C_{2}|x-y|^{2}
$$

With a slight abuse of notation, when there is no confusion, we use the notation $\mu_{t}^{(k)}:=$ $\mu^{(k)}\left(t, X_{t}\right)$ and $\sigma_{t}:=\sigma\left(t, X_{t}\right)$.

While the experts have differing views - in particular they disagree on the drift of $X-$ an agent wishes to combine the opinions of these experts and assigns each expert a weight $\pi=\left(\pi_{1}, \ldots, \pi_{K}\right)$ with $\pi_{k} \in[0,1], k \in \mathcal{K}$, and $\sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k}=1$. That is, the agent aims at reflecting the experts' opinions and incorporating them with their own belief into a combined probability measure $\mathbb{Q}$, which we call the combined model. The agent's beliefs are specified as follows: for functions $g: \mathbb{R}_{+} \times \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ and $f: \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$ the agent wishes to ensure that under a probability measure $\mathbb{Q}$ their beliefs

$$
\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}}\left[f\left(X_{T}\right)\right]=0 \quad \text { and } \quad \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}}\left[\int_{0}^{T} g\left(u, X_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u\right]=0
$$

are satisfied. Here, and in the sequel, we use the notation $\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}}[\cdot]$ to denote expectation under the agent's combined model. If $X_{T}$ is univariate and continuously distributed, the choice $f(x)=\mathbb{1}_{\{x<q\}}-\alpha, \alpha \in(0,1)$, for example, corresponds to the agent requiring that the Value-at-Risk (VaR) at level $\alpha$ of the combined model equals to $q$. The weights $\pi$ could be, e.g., obtained by computing the posterior probability that the data the agent is using stems from expert- $k$ 's model.

We propose that the agent combines the models by finding the (weighted) Kullback-Leibler (KL) barycentre of the expert models subject to the agent's constraints. Before presenting the formal optimisation problem, we need some conditions on the set of experts' probability measures that the agent aims to combine. The following is a standing assumption in the paper.

Assumption 2.2 (Compatibility of Expert Models). For every $k \in \mathcal{K}$,

$$
\mathbb{E}^{\mathfrak{p}^{(k)}}\left[e^{\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left|\gamma_{t}^{(k)}\right| \gamma_{\mathrm{d}} t}\right]<\infty
$$

where $\mathbb{E}^{\mathfrak{p}^{(k)}}[\cdot]$ denotes expectation under the $k^{\text {th }}$ expert's model, $\gamma_{t}^{(k)}:=\sigma_{t}^{-1}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\bar{\mu}_{t}\right)$, and $\bar{\mu}_{t}:=\sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \mu_{t}^{(k)}$ - the average drift of the experts' models.

The average drift of the experts' models $\bar{\mu}_{t}$ characterises the probability measure $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$, which we term the "average drift measure" and which plays a central role in the exposition. Indeed by Theorem 1 in [22], the conditions in Assumption 2.2 imply that, for all $k \in \mathcal{K}$, $\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{P}^{(k)}}\left[\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}^{(k)}}\right]=1$, where the probability measure $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$ is defined via the Radon-Nikodym derivative

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}^{(k)}}:=e^{-\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left|\tilde{\gamma}_{t}^{(k)}\right|^{2} \mathrm{~d} t-\int_{0}^{T} \tilde{\gamma}^{(k) \mathrm{t}} \mathrm{d} W_{t}^{(k)}}
$$

Moreover, by Girsanov's Theorem, $\bar{W}:=\left(W_{t}^{(k)}+\int_{0}^{t} \tilde{\gamma}_{u}^{(k)} \mathrm{d} u\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$ is a $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$-Brownian motion, for every $k \in \mathcal{K}$. We also make use of the average drift function $\bar{\mu}(t, x):=\sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \mu^{(k)}(t, x)$.

We are now in a position to state the agent's optimisation problem:
(P)

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \inf _{\mathbb{Q} \in \mathbb{Q}} \sum_{k \in K} \pi_{k} \mathcal{H}\left[\mathbb{Q} \| \mathbb{P}^{(k)}\right], \quad \text { s.t. } \quad \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}}\left[\int_{0}^{T} g\left(u, X_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u\right]=0, \quad \text { and } \\
& \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}}\left[f\left(X_{T}\right)\right]=0
\end{aligned}
$$

where

$$
\mathcal{H}\left[\mathbb{Q} \| \mathbb{P}^{(k)}\right]:=\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{P}^{(k)}}\left[\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}^{(k)}} \log \frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}}{\mathrm{~d} \mathbb{P}^{(k)}}\right]
$$

denotes the KL divergence of $\mathbb{Q}$ relative to $\mathbb{P}^{(k)}$ and $\mathcal{Q}$ is the set of probability measures parametrised as

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathcal{Q}:=\left\{\mathbb{Q}[\theta] \left\lvert\, \frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\theta]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\right.\right.=\exp \left\{-\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left|\tilde{\lambda}_{t}\right|^{2} \mathrm{~d} t-\int_{0}^{T} \tilde{\lambda}_{t}^{2} \mathrm{~d} \bar{W}_{t}\right\} \\
& \text { where } \quad \tilde{\lambda}_{t}:=\sigma_{t}^{-1}\left(\bar{\mu}_{t}-\theta_{t}\right) \\
& \theta:=\left(\theta_{t}\right)_{t \in[0, T]} \text { is an } \mathcal{F} \text {-adapted process, } \\
& \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\exp \left\{\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left|\tilde{\lambda}_{t}\right|^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right\}\right]<\infty, \text { and } \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\theta]}\left[\sup _{t \in[0, T]}\left|X_{t}\right|^{2}\right]<\infty\}
\end{aligned}
$$

By Theorem 1 in [22], the condition $\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[e^{\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left|\tilde{\lambda}_{t}\right|^{2} \mathrm{~d} t}\right]<\infty$ in the set $\mathcal{Q}$ ensures that $\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\theta]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\right]=1$.

Figure 1 provides a visualisation of problem (P). The left panel shows that we first change to the mean drift measure $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$, then to a measure $\mathbb{Q}[\theta]$ with arbitrary drift. The middle panel shows that we measure the KL divergence between the experts' measures $\left(\mathbb{P}^{(k)}\right)_{k \in \mathcal{K}}$ and $\mathbb{Q}[\theta]$, and the right panel shows that we aim to have this measure be within the set of expectation constraints $\mathcal{C}$ in problem (P).

Note that if expert-k's model satisfies $\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{P}^{(k)}}\left[\sup _{t \in[0, T]}\left|X_{t}\right|^{2}\right]<\infty$, then $\mathbb{P}^{(k)} \in \mathcal{Q}$. Similarly, if the average drift measure fulfils $\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\sup _{t \in[0, T]}\left|X_{t}\right|^{2}\right]<\infty$, then $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}] \in \mathcal{Q}$.

2.2. Value function. Next, we rewrite the agent's optimisation problem (P), which is an optimisation problem over probability measures, as an optimisation problem over admissible drifts of $X$. For this we define the set of admissible drifts $\theta$ of $X$ as the set of processes which induce a probability measure $\mathbb{Q}[\theta] \in \mathcal{Q}$. That is the set of admissible drifts is given by

$$
\mathcal{A}:=\left\{\theta: \Omega \times[0, T] \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^{d} \mid \mathbb{Q}[\theta] \in \mathcal{Q}\right\}
$$

Thus, the set $\mathcal{A}$ is the set of processes that generate the measures in the set $\mathcal{Q}$. Moreover, the set $\mathcal{A}$ and $\mathcal{Q}$ are isomorphic, one set is parametrised by $\mathcal{F}$-adapted processes, while the other is parametrised by probability measures. Furthermore, by Girsanov's Theorem, $W_{t}=\int_{0}^{t} \bar{\lambda}_{u} \mathrm{~d} u+\bar{W}_{t}$ is a $\mathbb{Q}[\theta]$-Brownian motion for each $k \in \mathcal{K}$, and therefore the $\mathbb{Q}[\theta]$-drift of $X$ is equal to $\theta$.

To rewrite optimisation problem ( P ) as an optimisation problem over the admissible strategies $\mathcal{A}$, we calculate the KL divergence from $\mathbb{Q}[\theta]$ to $\mathbb{P}^{(k)}$, and in particular the Radon-Nikodym derivative $\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\theta]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}^{(k)}}$. For any $\theta \in \mathcal{A}$, equivalently for any $\mathbb{Q}[\theta] \in \mathcal{Q}$, we have for all $k \in \mathcal{K}$, that

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\theta]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}^{(k)}} & =\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\theta]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]} \frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}^{(k)}} \\
& =e^{-\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left|\bar{\lambda}_{t}\right|^{2} \mathrm{~d} t-\int_{0}^{T} \bar{\lambda}_{t}^{\top} \mathrm{d} \bar{W}_{t}} e^{-\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left|\bar{\gamma}_{t}^{(k)}\right|^{2} \mathrm{~d} t-\int_{0}^{T} \bar{\gamma}^{(k)} \tau \mathrm{d} W_{t}^{(k)}} \\
& =e^{-\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left(\left|\bar{\lambda}_{t}\right|^{2}+\left|\bar{\gamma}_{t}^{(k)}\right|^{2}\right) \mathrm{d} t-\int_{0}^{T} \bar{\lambda}_{t}^{\top}\left(\mathrm{d} W_{t}^{(k)}+\bar{\gamma}_{t}^{(k)} \mathrm{d} t\right)-\int_{0}^{T} \bar{\gamma}^{(k)} \tau \mathrm{d} W_{t}^{(k)}} \\
& =e^{-\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left(\left|\bar{\lambda}_{t}\right|^{2}+2 \bar{\lambda}_{t}^{\top} \bar{\gamma}_{t}^{(k)}+\left|\bar{\gamma}_{t}^{(k)}\right|^{2}\right) \mathrm{d} t-\int_{0}^{T}\left(\sigma_{t}^{-1}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\theta_{t}\right)\right)^{\top} \mathrm{d} W_{t}^{(k)}} \\
& =e^{-\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\theta_{t}\right)^{\top} \Sigma_{t}^{-1}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\theta_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} t-\int_{0}^{T}\left(\sigma_{t}^{-1}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\theta_{t}\right)\right)^{\top} \mathrm{d} W_{t}^{(k)}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Thus, letting $\lambda_{t}^{(k)}:=\sigma_{t}^{-1}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\theta_{t}\right)$, Girsanov's Theorem implies that $\left(W_{t}^{(k)}+\int_{0}^{t} \lambda_{t}^{(k)} d t\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$ is a $\mathbb{Q}[\theta]$-Brownian motion. Thus, for each $k \in \mathcal{K}$, the KL divergence becomes

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{H}[\mathbb{Q}[\theta] \| \mathbb{P}^{(k)}] & =\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\theta]}[\log \frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\theta]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{P}^{(k)}}] \\
& =\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\theta]}\left[-\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\theta_{t}\right)^{\top} \Sigma_{t}^{-1}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\theta_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} t-\int_{0}^{T}\left(\sigma_{t}^{-1}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\theta_{t}\right)\right)^{\top} \mathrm{d} W_{t}^{(k)}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
& =\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\theta]}\left[-\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\theta_{t}\right)^{\top} \Sigma_{t}^{-1}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\theta_{t}\right) \mathrm{d} t\right. \\
& \left.\quad-\int_{0}^{T}\left(\sigma_{t}^{-1}\left(\mu_{t}^{(k)}-\theta_{t}\right)\right)^{\top}\left(\left(\mathrm{d} W_{t}^{(k)}+\lambda_{t}^{(k)} d t\right)-\lambda_{t}^{(k)} d t\right)\right] \\
& =\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\theta]}\left[\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T} \Delta \theta_{t}^{(k) \top} \Sigma_{t}^{-1} \Delta \theta_{t}^{(k)} \mathrm{d} t\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

where, we introduce the notation $\Delta \theta^{(k)}(t, x):=\theta(t, x)-\mu^{(k)}(t, x), \Delta \theta_{t}^{(k)}:=\Delta \theta^{(k)}\left(t, X_{t}\right)$, $\Sigma(t, x):=\sigma(t, x) \sigma(t, x)^{\top}$, and $\Sigma_{t}:=\Sigma\left(t, X_{t}\right)$.

Therefore, we rewrite optimisation problem ( P ) in terms of an optimisation over $\theta$ as follows

$$
\inf _{\theta \in \mathcal{A}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\theta]}\left[\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T} \Delta \theta_{t}^{(k) \top} \Sigma\left(t, X_{t}\right)^{-1} \Delta \theta_{t}^{(k)} \mathrm{d} t\right]
$$

subject to $\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\theta]}\left[\int_{0}^{T} g_{u} \mathrm{~d} u\right]=0$ and $\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\theta]}\left[f_{T}\right]=0$, where for simplicity of notation we write $g_{u}:=g\left(u, X_{u}\right)$ and $f_{T}:=f\left(X_{T}\right)$.

To solve this constrained optimisation problem, we introduce the associated Lagrangian with Lagrange multiplier $\eta:=\left(\eta_{0}, \eta_{1}\right) \in \mathbb{R}^{2}$, that is

$$
L_{\eta}[\theta \mid(t, x):=\mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\theta]}\left[\int_{t}^{T} \frac{1}{2} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \Delta \theta_{u}^{(k) \top} \Sigma_{u}^{-1} \Delta \theta_{u}^{(k)} \mathrm{d} u+\eta_{0} \int_{t}^{T} g_{u} \mathrm{~d} u+\eta_{1} f_{T}\right]
$$

where $\mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}}[\cdot]$ denotes expectation conditional on $X_{t}=x$. If we set $\eta=(0,0)$, then the problem reduces to finding the (pure) barycentre of the experts' models, i.e., without any constraints, which we discuss in Section 3. That is, we first discuss the pure barycentre problem and then tackle the full optimisation problem ( P ).

For fixed $\eta \in \mathbb{R}^{2}$, we define the value function

$$
L_{\eta}(t, x):=\inf _{\theta \in \mathcal{A}} L_{\eta}[\theta \mid(t, x)
$$

Note that for each $\eta$, the value function has an associated probability measure that attains the value function. Thus, when $\eta$ is chosen to bind the constraints the corresponding probability measure is the solution to optimisation problem (P). Thus, in a first step, we find for fixed $\eta$ the value function $L_{\eta}(t, x)$ and in a second step find the optimal $\eta$ such that the constraints are fulfilled.

Definition 2.1. The following Mahalanobis-like distance is an important ingredient in the solution of optimisation problem ( P )

$$
\varsigma(t, x):=\frac{1}{2} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \Delta \mu^{(k)}(t, x)^{\top} \Sigma^{-1}(t, x) \Delta \mu^{(k)}(t, x)
$$

where $\Delta \mu^{(k)}(t, x):=\mu^{(k)}(t, x)-\bar{\mu}(t, x)$.

3. The pure barycentre. In this section, we address the pure barycentre problem, i.e., the case when the agent has no additional beliefs that they wish to incorporate.

Definition 3.1 (Barycentre measure). Consider optimisation problem (P) without any constraints, whose solution we call the barycentre (probability) measure and denote by $\mathbb{Q}^{b}$, that is

$$
\mathbb{Q}^{b}:=\underset{\mathbb{Q} \in \mathcal{Q}}{\arg \min } \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \mathcal{H}[\mathbb{Q} \| \mathbb{P}^{(k)}]
$$

This problem is equivalent to solving (2.6) with $\eta=(0,0)$. The theorem below provides one of our key results, i.e., the drift under the barycentre measure, given in (3.2), and the associated value function, given in (3.1).

Theorem 3.2 (Barycentre Drift and Value Function). Let Assumptions 2.1 and 2.2 be enforced. Define the function $L_{0}:[0, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$, s.t.

$$
L_{0}(t, x):=-\log \mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]} \quad\left[e^{-\int_{t}^{T} \varsigma\left(u, X_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u}\right], \quad \forall(t, x) \in[0, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d}
$$

\end{aligned}
$$

where $\Gamma(t, x):=\frac{1}{2} \Delta \mu(t, x) \Sigma^{-1}(t, x) \Delta \mu(t, x)$ and, with a slight abuse of notation when we omit the subscript on $\Gamma,-$ we further omit the arguments $(t, x)$ the above PDEs.

Note that, for the case of two expert models and the choice of $\pi$ in the proposition statement, we have

$$
\varsigma=\frac{1}{2}\left((1-\varepsilon)\left(\mu^{(1)}-\bar{\mu}\right) \Sigma^{-1}\left(\mu^{(1)}-\bar{\mu}\right)+\varepsilon\left(\mu^{(2)}-\bar{\mu}\right) \Sigma^{-1}\left(\mu^{(2)}-\bar{\mu}\right)\right)
$$

and $\bar{\mu}=(1-\varepsilon) \mu^{(1)}+\varepsilon \mu^{(2)}=\mu^{(1)}+\varepsilon \Delta \mu$, where $\Delta \mu=\mu^{(2)}-\mu^{(1)}$. Hence,

$$
\mu^{(1)}-\bar{\mu}=-\varepsilon \Delta \mu, \quad \mu^{(2)}-\bar{\mu}=\mu^{(2)}-\mu^{(1)}-\varepsilon \Delta \mu=(1-\varepsilon) \Delta \mu
$$

Plugging these representation of $\mu^{(1)}$ and $\mu^{(2)}$ into $\varsigma$, we obtain

$$
\varsigma=\frac{1}{2}\left((1-\varepsilon) \varepsilon^{2} \Delta \mu \Sigma^{-1} \Delta \mu+\varepsilon(1-\varepsilon)^{2} \Delta \mu \Sigma^{-1} \Delta \mu\right)=\varepsilon(1-\varepsilon) \Gamma
$$

Inserting $\omega=\tilde{\omega}+r$ into (3.27a), and using (3.27b), we find that

$$
\begin{aligned}
0 & =\partial_{t}(\tilde{\omega}+r)+\bar{\mu}^{\top} \nabla(\tilde{\omega}+r)+\frac{1}{2} \operatorname{Tr}\left(\Sigma \nabla_{x}^{2}(\tilde{\omega}+r)\right)-\varepsilon(1-\varepsilon) \Gamma(\tilde{\omega}+r) \\
& =\partial_{t} r+\bar{\mu}^{\top} \nabla_{x} r+\frac{1}{2} \operatorname{Tr}\left(\Sigma \nabla_{x}^{2} r\right)-\varepsilon(1-\varepsilon) \Gamma r+\varepsilon(\Gamma(1-\tilde{\omega})+\varepsilon \Gamma \tilde{\omega})
\end{aligned}
$$

Next, define $\Upsilon(t, x):=\mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\int_{t}^{T} \Gamma_{u} \mathrm{~d} u\right]$ and note that $\tilde{\omega}(t, x)=1-\varepsilon \Upsilon(t, x)$, hence, the PDE (3.29) may be written as

$$
\partial_{t} r+\bar{\mu}^{\top} \nabla_{x} r+\frac{1}{2} \operatorname{Tr}\left(\Sigma \nabla_{x}^{2} r\right)-\varepsilon(1-\varepsilon) \Gamma r+\varepsilon^{2}(\Gamma+(1-\varepsilon) \Gamma \Upsilon)=0
$$

with terminal condition $r(T, x)=0$. Feynman-Kac then gives

$$
r(t, x)=\varepsilon^{2} \mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\int_{t}^{T} e^{-\varepsilon(1-\varepsilon) \int_{u}^{T} \Gamma_{s} \mathrm{~d} s}\left(\Gamma_{u}+(1-\varepsilon) \Gamma_{u} \Upsilon_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u\right]
$$

Recall that $\Gamma_{t}=\frac{1}{2} \Delta \mu_{t} \Sigma^{-1} \Delta \mu_{t}$, and as $\Sigma$ is strictly positive definite, $\Gamma_{t}>0$ a.s. Hence, for $\varepsilon \in[0,1]$, we have that

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left|\mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\int_{t}^{T} e^{-\varepsilon(1-\varepsilon) \int_{u}^{T} \Gamma_{s} \mathrm{~d} s}\left(\Gamma_{u}+\left(1-\varepsilon\right) \Gamma_{u} \Upsilon_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u\right]\right| \\
& \leq \mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\left|\int_{t}^{T} e^{-\varepsilon(1-\varepsilon) \int_{u}^{T} \Gamma_{s} \mathrm{~d} s}\left(\Gamma_{u}+\left(1-\varepsilon\right) \Gamma_{u} \Upsilon_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u\right|\right] \\
& \leq \mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\int_{0}^{T}\left(\left|\Gamma_{u}\right|+\left|\Gamma_{u} \Upsilon_{u}\right|\right) \mathrm{d} u\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, due to the bound (3.25), we have that

$$
\lim _{\varepsilon \downarrow 0}\left|\frac{r(t, x)}{\varepsilon}\right|=\lim _{\varepsilon \downarrow 0} \varepsilon\left|\mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\int_{t}^{T} e^{-\varepsilon(1-\varepsilon) \int_{u}^{T} \Gamma_{s} \mathrm{~d} s}\left(\Gamma_{u}+\left(1-\varepsilon\right) \Gamma_{u} \Upsilon_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u\right]\right|=0
$$

and the result follows.

Corollary 3.5 (Perturbed Drift.). Let the assumptions in Proposition 3.4 hold. Then the drift on the barycentre model with two experts and weights $\pi^{(1)}=1-\varepsilon, \pi^{(2)}=\varepsilon$ is

$$
\theta_{0, t}=\mu_{t}^{(1)}+\varepsilon\left(\Delta \mu_{t}-\Sigma_{t} \nabla_{x}\left(\mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\int_{t}^{T} \Delta \mu_{s}^{\top} \Sigma_{s}^{-1} \Delta \mu_{s} \mathrm{~d} s\right]\right)\right)+o(\varepsilon)
$$

Proof. The result follows immediately from the optimal drift (3.2) from Theorem 3.2 and Proposition 3.4.
3.2. Ornstein-Uhlenbeck experts' processes. In this section, we provide an example for a class of Ornstein-Uhlenbeck (OU) processes that allow for semi-explicit solutions - up to the solution of a Ricatti ordinary differential equation (ODE). To this end, Suppose that $d=1$ and that $\mu^{(k)}(t, x)=a_{t}^{(k)}-b_{t}^{(k)} x$ and $\sigma(t, x)=\sigma_{t} \geq \varepsilon$ (for some $\varepsilon>0$ ) where $a_{t}^{(k)}, b_{t}^{(k)}$, and $\sigma_{t}$ are bounded deterministic functions of time, for all $k \in \mathcal{K}$. Then we have that

$$
\varsigma(t, x)=\frac{1}{2 \sigma^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k}\left(\alpha_{t}^{(k)}-\beta_{t}^{(k)} x\right)^{2}
$$

where $\alpha_{t}^{(k)}:=a_{t}^{(k)}-\bar{a}_{t}, \bar{a}_{t}:=\sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} a_{t}^{(k)}, \beta_{t}^{(k)}:=b_{t}^{(k)}-\bar{b}_{t}$, and $\bar{b}_{t}:=\sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} b_{t}^{(k)}$. We further assume, without loss of generality, that at least one $\beta^{(k)} \neq 0$ - otherwise, $\varsigma$ is a constant and, hence, from Proposition 3.3, $\mathbb{Q}^{b}=\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$, i.e., the barycentre model is the one with the drift equal to the average of the experts' drifts.

We next aim to find $L_{0}(t, x)$ in (3.1) and subsequently, the optimal drift $\theta_{0}$ in (3.2).
Proposition 3.6. The drift in the barycentre model for the expert models specified above is given by

$$
\theta_{0, t}=\bar{\mu}_{t}+\sigma_{t}^{2}\left(\mathfrak{b}_{t}+\mathfrak{c}_{t} X_{t}\right)
$$

where $\mathfrak{c}_{t}$ solves the Ricatti equation

$$
\dot{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}-\bar{b}_{t} \mathfrak{c}_{t}+\frac{1}{2} \sigma_{t}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{t}^{2}-\zeta_{t}=0, \quad \mathfrak{c}_{T}=0
$$

$\zeta_{t}:=\frac{1}{2 \sigma^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k}\left(\beta_{t}^{(k)}\right)^{2}$ and $\mathfrak{b}_{t}$ is given by

$$
\mathfrak{b}_{t}=\int_{t}^{T}\left(\bar{a}_{s} \mathfrak{c}_{s}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{s}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \alpha_{s}^{(k)} \beta_{s}^{(k)}\right) e^{\int_{t}^{s}\left(\sigma_{a}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{s}-\bar{b}_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u} \mathrm{~d} s
$$

Moreover, $\mathfrak{c}_{t}$ and $\mathfrak{b}_{t}$ remain bounded on the domain $t \in[0, T]$.
Proof. Define $\omega(t, x):=\mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[e^{-\int_{t}^{T} \varsigma\left(t, X_{t}\right) d t}\right]$, Feynman-Kac formula implies that $\omega(t, x)$ satisfies the PDE (where we suppress the arguments $(t, x)$ )

$$
\partial_{t} \omega+\left(\bar{a}_{t}-\bar{b}_{t} x\right) \partial_{x} \omega+\frac{1}{2} \sigma^{2} \partial_{x x} \omega=\varsigma \omega, \quad \omega(T, x)=1
$$

As this is an affine PDE, it admits the solution of the form $\omega(t, x)=e^{\mathfrak{a}_{t}+\mathfrak{b}_{t} x+\frac{1}{2} \mathfrak{c}_{t} x^{2}}$, where $\mathfrak{a}_{t}$, $\mathfrak{b}_{t}$, and $\mathfrak{c}_{t}$ are deterministic functions of time, such that $\mathfrak{a}_{T}=\mathfrak{b}_{T}=\mathfrak{c}_{T}=0$. Plugging this form into (3.41), we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
\left(\dot{\mathfrak{a}}_{t}+\dot{\mathfrak{b}}_{t} x+\dot{\mathfrak{c}}_{t} x^{2}\right) & +\left(\bar{a}_{t}-\bar{b}_{t} x\right)\left(\mathfrak{b}_{t}+\mathfrak{c}_{t} x\right) \\
& +\frac{1}{2} \sigma_{t}^{2}\left(\mathfrak{c}_{t}+\left(\mathfrak{b}_{t}+\mathfrak{c}_{t} x\right)^{2}\right)=\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k}\left(\alpha_{t}^{(k)}-\beta_{t}^{(k)} x\right)^{2}
\end{aligned}
$$

Collecting terms that are constant in $x$, terms that are linear in $x$, and terms that are quadratic in $x$, we have

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(\dot{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}-\bar{b}_{t} \mathfrak{c}_{t}+\frac{1}{2} \sigma_{t}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{t}^{2}-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k}\left(\beta_{t}^{(k)}\right)^{2}\right) x^{2} \\
& +\left(\dot{\mathfrak{b}}_{t}-\bar{b}_{t} \mathfrak{b}_{t}+\bar{a}_{t} \mathfrak{c}_{t}+\sigma_{t}^{2} \mathfrak{b}_{t} \mathfrak{c}_{t}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \alpha_{t}^{(k)} \beta_{t}^{(k)}\right) x \\
& \quad+\left(\dot{\mathfrak{a}}_{t}+\bar{a}_{t} \mathfrak{b}_{t}+\frac{1}{2} \sigma_{t}^{2}\left(\mathfrak{c}_{t}+\mathfrak{b}_{t}^{2}\right)-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k}\left(\alpha_{t}^{(k)}\right)^{2}\right)=0
\end{aligned}
$$

As this must hold for all $t, x$, we obtain the system of ordinary differential equations

$$
\begin{array}{rlrl}
\dot{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}-\bar{b}_{t} \mathfrak{c}_{t}+\frac{1}{2} \sigma_{t}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{t}^{2}-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k}\left(\beta_{t}^{(k)}\right)^{2} & =0, & \mathfrak{c}_{T}=0 \\
\dot{\mathfrak{b}}_{t}+\left(\sigma_{t}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{t}-\bar{b}_{t}\right) \mathfrak{b}_{t}+\bar{a}_{t} \mathfrak{c}_{t}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \alpha_{t}^{(k)} \beta_{t}^{(k)} & =0, & \mathfrak{b}_{T}=0 \\
\dot{\mathfrak{a}}_{t}+\bar{a}_{t} \mathfrak{b}_{t}+\frac{1}{2} \sigma_{t}^{2}\left(\mathfrak{c}_{t}+\mathfrak{b}_{t}^{2}\right)-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k}\left(\alpha_{t}^{(k)}\right)^{2} & =0 & \mathfrak{a}_{T}=0
\end{array}
$$

We next prove that the $\mathfrak{c}_{t}$, which satisfies the Ricatti ODE (3.44), remains finite on the domain $t \in[0, T]$, and subsequently so do $\mathfrak{b}_{t}$ and $\mathfrak{a}_{t}$.

Accordingly, define $\alpha_{t}:=\int_{t}^{T} \bar{b}_{s} \mathrm{~d} s$, then

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t}\left(e^{\alpha_{t}} \mathfrak{c}_{t}\right)=e^{\alpha_{t}}\left(-\bar{b}_{t} \mathfrak{c}_{t}+\dot{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}\right)=e^{\alpha_{t}}\left(-\frac{1}{2} \sigma_{t}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{t}^{2}+\zeta_{t}\right)=-\frac{1}{2} e^{-\alpha_{t}} \sigma_{t}^{2}\left(e^{\alpha_{t}} \mathfrak{c}_{t}\right)^{2}+e^{\alpha_{t}} \zeta_{t}
$$

where

$$
\zeta_{t}:=\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{t}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k}\left(\beta_{t}^{(k)}\right)^{2}
$$

Let $\tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}:=e^{\alpha_{t}} \mathfrak{c}_{t}$, then we have

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t}\left(\tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}\right)=-\frac{1}{2} e^{-\alpha_{t}} \sigma_{t}^{2} \tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}^{2}+e^{\alpha_{t}} \zeta_{t}
$$

Defining, $\tilde{\sigma}_{t}:=\frac{1}{2} e^{-\alpha_{t}} \sigma_{t}^{2}$ and $\tilde{\zeta}_{t}:=e^{\alpha_{t}} \zeta_{t}$, we may re-write the above as

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t}\left(\tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}\right)=-\tilde{\sigma}_{t} \tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}^{2}+\tilde{\zeta}_{t}
$$

Note, the coefficient of $\tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}^{2}$ on the rhs is negative, consequently,

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t}\left(\tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}\right) \leq \tilde{\zeta}_{t} \quad \Rightarrow \quad \tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{T}-\tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t} \leq \int_{t}^{T} \tilde{\zeta}_{s} \mathrm{~d} s \quad \Rightarrow \quad \tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t} \geq-\int_{t}^{T} \tilde{\zeta}_{s} \mathrm{~d} s
$$

This provides a lower bound on $\tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}$ and hence a lower bound of $\mathfrak{c}_{t}$. Next, we obtain an upper bound. By (3.44), we deduce that $\left.\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} \tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}\right)\right|_{t=T}=\zeta_{T}>0$, hence there exists $\varepsilon>0$, s.t. $\forall t \in[T-\varepsilon, T), \tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}<0$.

Next, take $s=\sup \left\{u \in[0, T): \tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{u}=0\right\}$. Then, by (3.44), we have $\left.\left(\frac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{~d} t} \tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t}\right)\right|_{t=s}=\zeta_{s}>0$, and hence there exists $\varepsilon_{s}>0$, s.t. $\forall u \in\left[s-\varepsilon_{s}, s\right), \tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{u}<0$. Repeating this argument for all times $\left(s_{i}\right)_{i \in \mathbb{N}}$ s.t. $\tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{s_{i}}$ is zero, we conclude that $\tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t} \leq 0$ for all $t \in[0, T]$. Combining with the inequality (3.47), we have

$$
-\int_{t}^{T} \tilde{\zeta}_{s} \mathrm{~d} s \leq \tilde{\mathfrak{c}}_{t} \leq 0
$$

and therefore we arrive at the bound

$$
-e^{-\alpha_{t}} \int_{t}^{T} \tilde{\zeta}_{s} \mathrm{~d} s \leq \mathfrak{c}_{t} \leq 0
$$

As $\mathfrak{c}_{t}$ remains finite on the interval $t \in[0, T]$, we may solve for $\mathfrak{b}_{t}$ by using an integrating factor as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{d}{d t}\left(e^{-\int_{t}^{T}\left(\sigma_{u}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{u}-\tilde{b}_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u} \mathfrak{b}_{t}\right) & =\left(\left(\sigma_{t}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{t}-\tilde{b}_{t}\right) \mathfrak{b}_{t}+\dot{\mathfrak{b}}_{t}\right) e^{-\int_{t}^{T}\left(\sigma_{u}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{u}-\tilde{b}_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u} \\
& =-\left(\bar{a}_{t} \mathfrak{c}_{t}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{t}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \alpha_{t}^{(k)} \beta_{t}^{(k)}\right) e^{-\int_{t}^{T}\left(\sigma_{u}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{u}-\tilde{b}_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u}
\end{aligned}
$$

Integrating from $t$ to $T$, and as $\mathfrak{b}_{T}=0$, we obtain

$$
-e^{-\int_{t}^{T}\left(\sigma_{u}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{u}-\tilde{b}_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u} \mathfrak{b}_{t}=-\int_{t}^{T}\left(\bar{a}_{s} \mathfrak{c}_{s}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{s}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \alpha_{s}^{(k)} \beta_{s}^{(k)}\right) e^{-\int_{s}^{T}\left(\sigma_{u}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{u}-\tilde{b}_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u} \mathrm{~d} s
$$

which implies

$$
\mathfrak{b}_{t}=\int_{t}^{T}\left(\bar{a}_{s} \mathfrak{c}_{s}+\frac{1}{\sigma_{s}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k} \alpha_{s}^{(k)} \beta_{s}^{(k)}\right) e^{\int_{t}^{s}\left(\sigma_{u}^{2} \mathfrak{c}_{u}-\tilde{b}_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u} \mathrm{~d} s
$$

Then for $\mathfrak{a}_{t}$, integrating from $t$ to $T$, and as $\mathfrak{a}_{T}=0$, we obtain

$$
\mathfrak{a}_{t}=\int_{t}^{T}\left(\bar{a}_{s} \mathfrak{b}_{s}+\frac{1}{2} \sigma_{s}^{2}\left(\mathfrak{c}_{s}+\mathfrak{b}_{s}^{2}\right)-\frac{1}{2 \sigma_{s}^{2}} \sum_{k \in \mathcal{K}} \pi_{k}\left(\alpha_{s}^{(k)}\right)^{2}\right) \mathrm{d} s
$$

Due to the boundedness on the coefficients $\left(a^{(k)}, b^{(k)}\right)_{k \in \mathcal{K}}$ and the established bound on $\mathfrak{c}$, we see that $\mathfrak{a}$ and $\mathfrak{b}$ are also bounded on the interval $[0, T]$.

Therefore, $L_{0}(t, x)=-\left(\mathfrak{a}_{t}+\mathfrak{b}_{t} x+\frac{1}{2} \mathfrak{c}_{t} x^{2}\right)$ and from (3.2) we obtain the stated result.

The next proposition establishes that this class of OU expert models satisfy the requirements of Theorem 3.2.

Proposition 3.7. For the expert models specified above, we have that $L_{0} \in \mathcal{C}^{1,2}([0, T) \times$ $\mathbb{R}^{d} ; \mathbb{R}) \cap \mathcal{C}^{0}\left([0, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d} ; \mathbb{R}\right)$ and has at most quadratic growth, and

$$
\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[e^{\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left|\bar{\lambda}_{0, u}\right|^{2} \mathrm{~d} u}\right]<+\infty, \quad \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}\left[\theta_{0}\right]}\left[\sup _{t \in[0, T]}\left|X_{t}\right|^{2}\right]<+\infty
$$

where $\bar{\lambda}_{0, t}:=\sigma_{t}^{-1}\left(\bar{\mu}_{t}-\theta_{0, t}\right)$ and

$$
\theta_{0, t}:=\bar{\mu}_{t}-\Sigma_{t} \nabla_{x} L_{0}\left(t, X_{t}\right)
$$

Proof. First, form Proposition 3.6, we see that $L_{0}$ satisfies the properties in the proposition statement. Next, there exists $C$, s.t.,

$$
\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}\left[\theta_{0}\right]}\left[\sup _{t \in[0, T]}\left|X_{t}\right|^{2}\right] \leq C \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}\left[\theta_{0}\right]}\left[\int_{0}^{T} d[X, X]_{t}\right]=C \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}\left[\theta_{0}\right]}\left[\int_{0}^{T} \sigma_{t}^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right]<\infty
$$

Next, by Proposition 3.6, $\bar{\lambda}_{0, t}=\sigma_{t} \nabla_{x} L_{0}\left(t, X_{t}\right)=-\sigma_{t}\left(\mathfrak{b}_{t}+\mathfrak{c}_{t} X_{t}\right)$, therefore,

$$
\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[e^{\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left|\bar{\lambda}_{0, u}\right|^{2} \mathrm{~d} u}\right]=\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[e^{\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T} \sigma_{u}^{2}\left(\mathfrak{b}_{u}+\mathfrak{c}_{u} X_{u}\right)^{2} \mathrm{~d} u}\right]
$$

Define $h(t, x):=\mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[e^{\frac{1}{2} \int_{t}^{T} \sigma_{u}^{2}\left(\mathfrak{b}_{u}+\mathfrak{c}_{u} X_{u}\right)^{2} \mathrm{~d} u}\right]$, then $h$ satisfies the PDE

$$
\begin{cases}\partial_{t} h+\bar{\mu} \partial_{x} h+\frac{1}{2} \sigma^{2} \partial_{x x} h+\frac{1}{2} \sigma^{2}(\mathfrak{b}+\mathfrak{c} x)^{2} & =0 \\ h(T, x) & =1\end{cases}
$$

As this is an affine PDE, it admits a solution of the form $h(t, x)=e^{\mathfrak{l}_{t}+\mathfrak{f}_{t} x+\mathfrak{g}_{t} x^{2}}$, where $\mathfrak{l}, \mathfrak{f}$, and $\mathfrak{g}$ are all deterministic functions of time. As $\bar{\mu}, \sigma, \mathfrak{b}$, and $\mathfrak{c}$ are all bounded, using similar arguments as in the proof of Proposition 3.6, we find that $\mathfrak{l}, \mathfrak{f}$, and $\mathfrak{g}$ are all bounded for all $t \in[0, T]$. Therefore, we conclude $\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[e^{\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left|\bar{\lambda}_{0, u}\right|^{2} \mathrm{~d} u}\right]=h(T, x)<\infty$.
4. The case with beliefs. In this section, we extend the barycentre discussed above to the case when the agent has additional beliefs that they wish to incorporate. That is, we solve (P).
4.1. Optimal model. Beliefs may be incompatible with the experts' models. To avoid this scenario, we make the following assumption, which guarantees that the constraints imposed by the agent are feasible.

Assumption 4.1 (Feasibility of constraints). A solution to the following set of equations exists

$$
\nabla_{\eta} \log \left(\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}^{b}}\left[e^{-\eta_{0} \int_{0}^{T} g_{t} \mathrm{~d} t-\eta_{1} f_{T}}\right]\right)=0
$$

Lemma 4.1. If the random variable $Y:=\left(\int_{0}^{T} g_{t} \mathrm{~d} t, f_{T}\right)^{\top}$ is $\mathbb{Q}^{b}$-non-degenerate:

$$
\forall c \in \mathbb{R}^{2}, \quad \mathbb{Q}^{b}(\{\omega: Y(\omega)=c\})<1
$$

i.e., $Y$ is $\mathbb{Q}^{b}$-a.s. not constant, then if there exists a solution to (4.1), it is unique and we denote this unique solution by $\eta^{*}:=\left(\eta_{0}^{*}, \eta_{1}^{*}\right)$.

Proof. Let $K(\eta):=\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}^{b}}\left[e^{-\eta \cdot Y}\right]$. We first show that $K(\eta)$ is strictly convex. To this end, note that

$$
\nabla_{\eta} K(\eta)=-\frac{\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}^{b}}\left[Y e^{-\eta \cdot Y}\right]}{\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}^{b}}\left[e^{-\eta \cdot Y}\right]}=-\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}_{0}^{b}}[Y]
$$

and

$$
\begin{aligned}
\nabla_{\eta \eta}^{2} K(\eta) & =\frac{\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}^{b}}\left[Y Y^{\top} e^{-\eta \cdot Y}\right]}{\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}^{b}}\left[e^{-\eta \cdot Y}\right]}-\frac{\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}^{b}}\left[Y e^{-\eta \cdot Y}\right] \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}^{b}}\left[Y^{\top} e^{-\eta \cdot Y}\right]}{\left(\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}^{b}}\left[e^{-\eta \cdot Y}\right]\right)^{2}} \\
& =\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}_{0}^{b}}\left[Y Y^{\top}\right]-\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}_{0}^{b}}[Y] \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}_{0}^{b}}\left[Y^{\top}\right] \\
& =\operatorname{Cov}^{\mathbb{Q}_{0}^{b}}[Y]
\end{aligned}
$$

where the measure $\mathbb{Q}_{\eta}^{b}$ is defined by the Radon-Nikodym derivative

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}_{\eta}}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}^{b}}=\frac{e^{-\eta \cdot Y}}{\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}^{b}}\left[e^{-\eta \cdot Y}\right]}
$$

and $\operatorname{Cov}^{\mathbb{Q}_{0}^{b}}[Y]$ denotes the $\mathbb{Q}_{\eta}^{b}$-covariance matrix of $Y$. As $Y$ is $\mathbb{Q}_{\eta}^{b}$-non-degenerate and as $\mathbb{Q}_{\eta}^{b}$ and $\mathbb{Q}^{b}$ are equivalent, it is also $\mathbb{Q}_{\eta}^{b}$-non-degenerate. Hence, $\operatorname{Cov}^{\mathbb{Q}_{0}^{b}}[Y]$ and therefore $\nabla_{\eta \eta}^{2} K(\eta)$, is strictly positive definite. Therefore $K(\eta)$ is strictly convex. Consequently, if a minimiser of $K$ exists, it is unique, and solves the first order condition $\nabla_{\eta} K(\eta)=0$. Thus, there can be at most one solution to (4.1).

The theorem below provides our next key result the solution to optimisation problem (P), i.e., the drift under the optimal measure, given in (4.6), and the associated value function, given in (4.5).

Theorem 4.2 (Optimal Drift and Value Function with Beliefs). Let Assumptions 2.1 and 2.2 be satisfied. Take $\eta \in \mathbb{R}^{2}$ such that $\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}^{b}}\left[\exp \left\{-\eta_{0} \int_{0}^{T} g_{t} \mathrm{~d} t-\eta_{1} f_{T}\right\}\right]<+\infty$.

Define the function $L_{\eta}:[0, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}$, s.t.

$$
L_{\eta}(t, x):=-\log \mathbb{E}_{t, x}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[e^{-\int_{t}^{T}\left(\iota\left(u, X_{u}\right)+\eta_{0} g_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u-\eta_{1} f_{T}}\right], \quad \forall(t, x) \in[0, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d}
$$

Suppose that $L_{\eta} \in \mathcal{C}^{1,2}\left([0, T) \times \mathbb{R}^{d} ; \mathbb{R}\right) \cap \mathcal{C}^{0}\left([0, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d} ; \mathbb{R}\right)$ and has at most quadratic growth, i.e. there exists $C \in \mathbb{R}_{+}$s.t. $\left|L_{\eta}(t, x)\right| \leq C\left(1+|x|^{2}\right)$ for all $(t, x) \in[0, T] \times \mathbb{R}^{d}$. 5. Deep learning algorithms. In low dimensions, such as $d=1$ or 2 , we can approximate the solution to optimisation problem ( P ) using finite-difference methods by (a) solving for the optimal Lagrange multipliers by solving the appropriate PDE, and (b) once the optimal Lagrange multipliers are obtained, using a second finite-difference scheme to approximate $\omega(t, x)$ which then provides, through (4.6), the optimal drift. In higher dimensions, however, finite-difference and other traditional PDE methods run into difficulties due to the curse of dimensionality. Hence, to overcome the curse of dimensionality, we propose two deep learning algorithms to approximate the solution to optimisation problem ( P ). The first deep learning algorithm approximates the drift of a candidate measure and uses the difference in the RN densities as a loss function. The second deep learning algorithm approximates a transformation of the value function, specifically $\omega(t, x)=e^{-L_{\eta^{*}}(t, x)}$, by leveraging the notion of elicitability which allows one to estimate conditional statistics of a distribution function, e.g., a conditional expectation, via a strictly convex optimization problem. Often when elicitability is used to estimate conditional statistics, a parametric assumption on the dependence of the conditioning variables are made, e.g., the dependence is assumed to be linear, quadratic, or polynomial in the conditioning variables. Rather, when utilizing neural networks, due to their universal approximation ability, parametric assumptions are not necessary. While neural networks and deep learning approaches have been utilised in a variety in financial modelling contexts, the specific algorithms presented here are tailored to the constrained KL barycentre problem that we pose. In this sense, the algorithms are novel. We make use of the fact that neural networks are universal approximators, but tune the algorithms to providing approximations to our specific problem formulation.
5.1. Learning the optimal drift. In this section, we develop a deep learning approach that directly learns the stochastic exponential - the RN derivative - that drives the measure change from $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$ to the optimal measure $\mathbb{Q}\left[\theta_{\eta^{*}}\right]$. For this, we write the measure change from

a candidate measure $\mathbb{Q}[\theta]$ to $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$ as

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\theta]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}=\exp \left\{-\frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{T}\left|\tilde{\lambda}\left(t, X_{t}\right)\right|^{2} \mathrm{~d} t-\int_{0}^{T} \tilde{\lambda}\left(t, X_{t}\right)^{\top} \mathrm{d} \bar{W}_{t}\right\}
$$

where $\tilde{\lambda}(t, x):=\sigma^{-1}(t, x)(\bar{\mu}(t, x)-\theta(t, x))$ and $\left(\bar{W}_{t}\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$ are $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$-Brownian motions. To approximate the optimal measure, we parametrise the drift process (under the candidate measure $\mathbb{Q}[\theta])\left(\theta_{t}\right)_{t \in[0, T]}$ by a neural network with parameters $\mathfrak{a}$, and write this as $\theta[\mathfrak{a}]\left(t, X_{t}\right)$ - which takes $t$ and $X_{t}$ as inputs and outputs the drift at time $t$ and state $X_{t}$.

The approach we take to learning the drift is as follows. First, introduce a time grid $\left\{t_{0}, \ldots, t_{N}\right\}$, where $t_{i}:=i \Delta t, i=0, \ldots, N$, and $\Delta t:=\frac{T}{N}$. Second, simulate sample paths of Brownian motions under the measure $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$, denoted as $\bar{W}_{t_{0}}, \bar{W}_{t_{1}}, \ldots, \bar{W}_{t_{N}}$ and write their increments as $\Delta \bar{W}_{t_{i}}:=\bar{W}_{t_{i+1}}-\bar{W}_{t_{i}}$. Third, use an Euler-Maruyama discretisation of $X$, which we denote $\tilde{X}$, via

$$
\tilde{X}_{t_{i}}=\tilde{X}_{t_{i-1}}+\bar{\mu}_{t_{i-1}} \Delta t+\sigma_{t_{i-1}} \Delta \bar{W}_{t_{i}}
$$

where $\bar{\mu}_{t_{i-1}}:=\bar{\mu}\left(t_{i-1}, \tilde{X}_{t_{i-1}}\right)$ and $\sigma_{t_{i-1}}:=\sigma\left(t_{i-1}, \tilde{X}_{t_{i-1}}\right)$ - with a slight abuse of notation we do not place tildes on $\bar{\mu}$ and $\sigma$, despite them being evaluated along the Euler-Maruyama discretisation of $X$. From these sample paths, for the current estimate of the parameters $\mathfrak{a}$, we then obtain sample paths of $\theta[\mathfrak{a}]$ by evaluating the neural network for $\theta[\mathfrak{a}]$ along the sample paths of $\tilde{X}$ that we already obtained, i.e., by evaluating $\theta_{t_{i}}^{\mathfrak{a}}:=\theta\left[\mathfrak{a}\right]\left(t_{i}, \tilde{X}_{t_{i}}\right)$. We then evaluate

$$
\tilde{\lambda}_{t_{i-1}}=\sigma_{t_{i-1}}^{-1}\left(\bar{\mu}_{t_{i-1}}-\theta_{t_{i-1}}^{\mathfrak{a}}\right)
$$

for all $i=0, \ldots, N$, across all sample paths.
With the sample paths of $X$ under $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$, we then obtain the Lagrange multipliers by solving for the root of the equations

$$
\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}\left[\theta_{\mathrm{a}}\right]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]} f_{T}\right]=0 \quad \text { and } \quad \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}\left[\theta_{\mathrm{a}}\right]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]} \int_{0}^{T} g_{\mathrm{u}} \mathrm{~d} u\right]=0
$$

Note that the above quantities can be approximated from samples under the fixed measure $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$. The algorithm for finding $\eta^{*}$ is presented in Algorithm 5.1. Note that while Assumption 4.1 gives $\eta^{*}$ as a solution to a set of non-linear equations, the expectations are with respect to the barycentre measure $\mathbb{Q}^{\mathfrak{b}}$. Thus, to utilise Assumption 4.1, we need samples paths under $\mathbb{Q}^{\mathfrak{b}}$, which require to solve for the barycentre model. The above approach makes use of the readily available average drift model, which is straightforwardly obtained from simulations of the experts' models.

Finally, to learn the optimal drift, we use the loss function

$$
\mathfrak{L}[\theta[\mathfrak{a}]]:=\mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\left(\log \left(\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\theta[\mathfrak{a}]]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\right)-\log \left(\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}\left[\theta_{\eta^{*}}\right]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\right)\right)^{2}\right]
$$

with $\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\theta[\mathfrak{a}]]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}$ given in (5.1) and $\frac{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}\left[\theta_{\eta^{*}}\right]}{\mathrm{d} \mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}$ given in Proposition 4.4. All terms in the loss function may be approximated by simulating under the single measure $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$. We update the parameters $\mathfrak{a}$ using gradient descent, via $\mathfrak{a} \leftarrow \mathfrak{a}-r_{\mathfrak{a}} \nabla_{\mathfrak{a}} \mathfrak{L}[\theta[\mathfrak{a}]]$, where $r_{\mathfrak{a}}$ is a learning rate.             \(\mathfrak{L}[\omega[\boldsymbol{\theta}]:=\frac{1}{M} \sum_{\substack{m \in \mathfrak{M} \\ i=0, \ldots, N-1}}\left(\omega[\boldsymbol{\theta}]\left(t_{i}, \bar{X}_{t_{i}}^{[m]}\right)-e^{-\zeta_{i}^{[m]}-\eta_{1}^{*} f\left(\bar{X}_{t_{N}}^{[m]}\right)}\right)^{2} \Delta t ;\right.\)
```
        update \(\left.\boldsymbol{\theta} \leftarrow \boldsymbol{\theta}-r_{\theta} \nabla_{\theta} \mathfrak{L}[\omega[\boldsymbol{\theta}]]\right\);
    while not converged;
```

$$
\mathfrak{L}[\omega[\mathfrak{o}]]:=\underset{\mathfrak{o}}{\arg \min } \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\int_{0}^{T}\left(\omega[\mathfrak{o}]\left(t, X_{t}\right)-e^{-\int_{t}^{T}\left(\zeta\left(u, X_{u}\right)+\eta_{0}^{*} g_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u-\eta_{1}^{*} f_{T}}\right)^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right]
$$

$$
\omega=\underset{h}{\arg \min } \mathbb{E}^{\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]}\left[\int_{0}^{T}\left(h\left(t, X_{t}\right)-e^{-\int_{t}^{T}\left(\zeta\left(u, X_{u}\right)+\eta_{0}^{*} g_{u}\right) \mathrm{d} u-\eta_{1}^{*} f_{T}}\right)^{2} \mathrm{~d} t\right]
$$

where the minimum is taken over all square integrable functions $h: \mathbb{R}_{+} \times \mathbb{R}^{d} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}_{+}$; for more details see [14] and [23] Appendix C.

With the approximation of $\omega$ at hand, we obtain an estimate of the optimal drift using (4.6). Note that $\nabla_{x} L_{\eta}\left(t, X_{t}\right)$ can be obtained using backpropagation of $L_{\eta}\left(t, X_{t}\right)$ with respect to the input parameters $x$.

In implementation, we use the empirical estimator of the expectation by generating simulations of $X$ under $\mathbb{Q}[\bar{\mu}]$, using the same methodology as in Subsection 5.1, and then approximate the Riemann integrals in (5.3) using the same time discretisation as in the simulation of $X$. The detailed steps for estimating $\omega$ using the elicitability methodology are provided in Algorithm 5.3.

We conduct a comparison case study of the two algorithms in the next section.

7. Conclusions. We present an approach to combine expert models, based on minimisation of the weighted KL divergence between the experts' models and a candidate model, that incorporates the agent's beliefs in the form of expectation constraints. The proposed methodology may be suitable to combine models in a multitude of settings in mathematical finance ranging from climate finance, to volatility modelling, and high-frequency trading. Moreover the resulting optimal model can be deployed as a generative model for, e.g., a dynamic riskaware reinforcement learning approach to mitigating risks and optimising portfolio allocation $[10,23]$ or generating climate scenarios that feed into risk management for carbon planning $[17]$.

abstract:
We consider the problem where an agent aims to combine the views and insights
of different experts' models. Specifically, each expert proposes a diffusion
process over a finite time horizon. The agent then combines the experts' models
by minimising the weighted Kullback--Leibler divergence to each of the experts'
models. We show existence and uniqueness of the barycentre model and prove an
explicit representation of the Radon--Nikodym derivative relative to the
average drift model. We further allow the agent to include their own
constraints, resulting in an optimal model that can be seen as a distortion of
the experts' barycentre model to incorporate the agent's constraints. We
propose two deep learning algorithms to approximate the optimal drift of the
combined model, allowing for efficient simulations. The first algorithm aims at
learning the optimal drift by matching the change of measure, whereas the
second algorithm leverages the notion of elicitability to directly estimate the
value function. The paper concludes with an extended application to combine
implied volatility smile models that were estimated on different datasets.
